def: Lying toward the mesial plane; mesial. Internal angle (Geom.),an interior angle. See under Interior.-- Internal gear (Mach.), a gear in which the teeth project inwardfrom the rim instead of outward.

Long exercised in anything, especially in military life and theduties of a soldier; long practiced or experienced; as, a veteranofficer or soldier; veteran skill.The insinuating eloquence and delicate flattery of veterandiplomatists and courtiers. Macaulay.
Full of grains; abounding with granular substances; granular.
Having or wearing a stole.After them flew the prophets, brightly stoled In shining lawn. G.Fletcher.
A polishing material made of potter's clay that has failed inbaking.
Worse. [Obs.]They say the world is much warre than it wont. Spenser.
One whose business it is to extract teeth with instruments; adentist. Shak.

To utter suddenly and unadvisedly; to divulge inconsiderately;to ejaculate; -- commonly with out.Others . . . can not hold, but blurt out, those words which afterwardthey forced to eat. Hakewill.To blurt at, to speak contemptuously of. [Obs.] Shak.
To cite; to summon. [Obs.]Our heralds now accited all that were Endamaged by the Elians.Chapman.
Tongued; having the tongue visible.Lions . . . represented as armed and langued gules. Cussans.
The for pump in the pit. Raymond.
